title: For Sale:  U.S. Springfield Model 1884 Trapdoor Cadet Rifle, Type One
postcontent:
The Model 1884 Cadet was manufactured from 1888 to 1893 with this example manufactured in 1890. The rifle is equipped with a Buffington rear sight and is marked on the top of the breechblock with number "39". The breechblock is marked "U.S./MODEL/1884" and the lock plate is marked with the eagle/shield motif along with "U.S./SPRINGFIELD" ahead of the hammer. The left rear side of the barrel is stamped with "V/P/eaglehead/P" proofs. The letter "A" is stamped on the top of the barrel at the breech. The oiled finished stock has a faint "SWP/1890" cartouche on the left side of the wrist. The stock has two barrel bands. The rifle has a button head cleaning rod, one piece trigger guard, and falls within the correct serial number range, all of which are indicative of the scarcer Type I U.S. Springfield Model 1884 Trapdoor Cadet. The Trapdoor Cadet Rifle offered for your consideration is in fine condition according to the antique firearms condition standards. The bore is in excellent condition and shows strong rifling, having been well preserved through the years. There is a light patina on the top of the reciever, and some finish missing from the lock, pictures can be provided of these minor cosmetic issues. Overall it is in fine condition with a good amount of finish remaining on the metal parts, and only minor dents in the stock. The "SWP/1890" cartouche is faint, but can still be seen. It has the original ramrod, and is marked on top of the reciever with the number "39". The number "39" was probably the rifle number, or rack number of the rifle, for when it was being used as a Cadet Rifle. This Type I U.S. Springfield Model 1884 Trapdoor Cadet Rifle offered for your consideration is scarce and would make an excellent addition to your collection because of exceptional condition, specifically the bore.
